<div class="show-content user_content clearfix enhanced" data-resource-type="wiki_page.body" data-resource-id="434" data-lti-page-content="true">
  
    <h1 class="page-title">Using AI to help with testing</h1>
  
  <div id="todo-date-mount-point"></div>
  
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #141312 0%, #2a2622 100%); color: white; padding: 60px 20px; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 40px;">
<h1 style="font-size: 2.5em; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Using AI to help with testing</h1>
<p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin: 0 auto; max-width: 800px;">Testing can feel overwhelming. Writing good tests requires understanding what to test, how to structure tests, and identifying edge cases you might not have thought of. While it might be tempting to have AI generate all your tests, that approach wonŌĆÖt help you learn and grow as a developer.</p>
</div>
<div style="max-width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 20px;">
<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 5px solid #F09B08; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 40px; border-radius: 8px;">
<p style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.1em; color: #141312;">The good news is that AI can be a supportive learning partner that helps you understand testing principles better, improve your existing tests, and develop a testing mindset. This chapter focuses on using AI to enhance your testing skills rather than replace them.</p>
</div>
<div style="background-color: white; border: 2px solid #F09B08; border-radius: 12px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 40px;">
<h2 style="color: #f09b08; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em; margin-bottom: 20px;">In this chapter we look at specific scenarios:</h2>
<div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 20px; margin-top: 20px;">
<div style="flex: 1; min-width: 300px; background-color: #f8f9fa; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #F09B08;">
<h3 style="color: #141312; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.3em;">1. Understanding What to Test</h3>
</div>
